SIMPLE: sign
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sign
<hw>Sign</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>signe</ets>, L.
<ets>signum</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>segen</ets>, <ets>segn</ets>, a sign,
standard, banner, also fr. L. <ets>signum</ets>. Cf. <er>Ensign</er>,
<er>Resign</er>, <er>Seal</er> a stamp, <er>Signal</er>,
<er>Signet</er>.]</ety> <def>That by which anything is made known or
represented; that which furnishes evidence; a mark; a token; an
indication; a proof.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A remarkable
event, considered by the ancients as indicating the will of some deity;
a prodigy; an omen.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An event considered by the
Jews as indicating the divine will, or as manifesting an interposition
of the divine power for some special end; a miracle; a wonder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through mighty <qex>signs</qex> and wonders, by the power of the
Spirit of God.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xv. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It shall come to pass, if they will not believe thee, neither
hearken to the voice of the first <qex>sign</qex>, that they will
believe the voice of the latter <qex>sign</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. iv.
8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Something serving to indicate the existence, or
preserve the memory, of a thing; a token; a memorial; a
monument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What time the fire devoured two hundred and fifty men, and they
became a <qex>sign</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xxvi. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Any symbol or emblem which prefigures, typifies, or
represents, an idea; a type; hence, sometimes, a picture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The holy symbols, or <qex>signs</qex>, are not barely
significative; but what they represent is as certainly delivered to us
as the symbols themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Brerewood.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Saint George of Merry England, the <qex>sign</qex> of victory.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>A word or a character regarded as the outward
manifestation of thought; as, words are the <xex>sign</xex> of
ideas.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>A motion, an action, or a gesture by
which a thought is expressed, or a command or a wish made
known.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They made <qex>signs</qex> to his father, how he would have him
called.</q> <rj><qau>Luke i. 62.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <def>Hence, one of the gestures of pantomime, or of a
language of a signs such as those used by the North American Indians, or
those used by the deaf and dumb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Educaters of the deaf distinguish between <xex>natural
signs</xex>, which serve for communicating ideas, and
<xex>methodical</xex>, or <xex>systematic</xex>, <xex>signs</xex>,
adapted for the dictation, or the rendering, of written language, word
by word; and thus the <xex>signs</xex> are to be distinguished from the
<xex>manual alphabet</xex>, by which words are spelled on the
fingers.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(h)</sd> <def>A military emblem carried on a banner or a
standard.</def> <au>Milton.</au> <sd>(i)</sd> <def>A lettered board, or
other conspicuous notice, placed upon or before a building, room, shop,
or office to advertise the business there transacted, or the name of the
person or firm carrying it on; a publicly displayed token or
notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shops were, therefore, distinguished by painted
<qex>signs</qex>, which gave a gay and grotesque aspect to the
streets.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(j)</sd> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The twelfth part of the
ecliptic or zodiac.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>signs</xex> are reckoned from the point of
intersection of the ecliptic and equator at the vernal equinox, and are
named, respectively, <stype>Aries</stype> (⟦Aries⟧),
<stype>Taurus</stype> (⟦Taurus⟧), <stype>Gemini</stype> (II),
<stype>Cancer</stype> (⟦Cancer⟧), <stype>Leo</stype> (⟦Leo⟧),
<stype>Virgo</stype> (⟦Virgo⟧), <stype>Libra</stype> (⟦Libra⟧),
<stype>Scorpio</stype> (⟦Scorpio⟧), <stype>Sagittarius</stype>
(⟦Sagittarius⟧), <stype>Capricornus </stype> (⟦Capricorn⟧),
<stype>Aquarius</stype> (⟦Aquarius⟧), <stype>Pisces</stype> (⟦Pisces⟧).
These names were originally the names of the constellations occupying
severally the divisions of the zodiac, by which they are still retained;
but, in consequence of the procession of the equinoxes, the signs have,
in process of time, become separated about 30 degrees from these
constellations, and each of the latter now lies in the sign next in
advance, or to the east of the one which bears its name, as the
constellation Aries in the sign Taurus, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(k)</sd> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>A character indicating the
relation of quantities, or an operation performed upon them; <as>as, the
<ex>sign</ex> + (plus); the <ex>sign</ex> -- (minus); the <ex>sign</ex>
of division ⟦divide⟧, and the like</as>.</def> <sd>(l)</sd>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An objective evidence of disease; that is, one
appreciable by some one other than the patient.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The terms <xex>symptom</xex> and and <xex>sign</xex> are
often used synonymously; but they may be discriminated. A
<xex>sign</xex> differs from a <xex>symptom</xex> in that the latter is
perceived only by the patient himself. The term <xex>sign</xex> is often
further restricted to the purely local evidences of disease afforded by
direct examination of the organs involved, as distinguished from those
evidence of general disturbance afforded by observation of the
temperature, pulse, etc. In this sense it is often called <xex>physical
sign</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(m)</sd> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Any character, as a flat, sharp,
dot, etc.</def> <sd>(n)</sd> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>That which, being
external, stands for, or signifies, something internal or spiritual; --
a term used in the Church of England in speaking of an ordinance
considered with reference to that which it represents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An outward and visible <qex>sign</qex> of an inward and spiritual
grace.</q> <rj><qau>Bk. of Common Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ See the Table of <er>Arbitrary Signs</er>, p.
1924.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sign manual</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>
<cd>The royal signature superscribed at the top of bills of grants and
letter patent, which are then sealed with the privy signet or great
seal, as the case may be, to complete their validity</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>The signature of one's name in one's own handwriting.</cd>
<au>Craig. Tomlins. Wharton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Token; mark; note; symptom; indication; signal;
symbol; type; omen; prognostic; presage; manifestation. See
<er>Emblem</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sign</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sign
<hw>Sign</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Signed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Signing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>seinen</ets> to bless,
originally, to make the sign of the cross over; in this sense fr. ASS.
<ets>segnian</ets> (from <ets>segn</ets>, n.), or OF.
<ets>seignier</ets>, F. <ets>signer</ets>, to mark, to sign (in sense
3), fr. L. <ets>signare</ets> to mark, set a mark upon, from
<ets>signum</ets>. See <er>Sign</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To represent by a sign; to make known in a typical or emblematic
manner, in distinction from speech; to signify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>signed</qex> to Browne to make his retreat.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a sign upon; to mark with a sign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We receive this child into the congregation of Christ's flock, and
do <qex>sign</qex> him with the sign of the cross.</q> <rj><qau>Bk. of
Com Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To affix a signature to; to ratify by hand or seal;
to subscribe in one's own handwriting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inquire the Jew's house out, give him this deed,⟦br⟧
And let him <qex>sign</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To assign or convey formally; -- used with
<xex>away</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To mark; to make distinguishable.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sign</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sign
<hw>Sign</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be a
sign or omen.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a sign or signal; to communicate directions
or intelligence by signs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Especially:</specif> <def>To communicate in
<er>sign language</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To write one's name, esp. as a token of assent,
responsibility, or obligation; <as>as, he <ex>signed</ex> in red
ink</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Signable</ent>⟦br⟧
